  <section class="py-16 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 max-w-4xl mx-auto border-t border-slate-800">
    <h2 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-white text-center mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      
      <!-- FAQ 1 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do optical illusions work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Optical illusions work because the brain does not passively record visual inputs. Instead, it creates predictions about the outside world based on prior experience, lighting, and angles. When an image contains mismatched inputs (such as specific contrasting stripes or shapes), the brain's top-down prediction conflicts with the physical layout, producing an illusion.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 2 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Why do optical illusions work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Illusions work because of evolutionary shortcuts. Processing every visual element in real-time requires immense energy and time. To react quickly, the brain takes shortcuts—like grouping lines together, assuming light comes from above, and adjusting colors to illumination. Illusions are simply the edge cases where these shortcuts fail.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 3 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do optical illusions trick the brain?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Illusions trick the brain by exploiting specialized visual neurons. For example, motion illusions use alternating light/dark contrast bands to overstimulate motion-selective neurons in area V5. Color illusions trick the color-constancy cells in area V4 by introducing ambiguous ambient light.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 4 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>What part of the brain sees optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Visual processing starts in the primary visual cortex (V1) at the back of the brain. From V1, signals split into area V4 (processing color and form) and area V5/MT (processing motion). High-level cognitive interpretations are resolved in the parietal and temporal lobes.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 5 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Are optical illusions bad for your eyes?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          No, optical illusions are completely harmless. They do not cause any physical damage to your eyes or brain. They simply showcase the natural boundaries of visual perception. If staring at highly repetitive motion lines causes mild eye strain, simply look away to rest your eyes.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 6 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Why do I see optical illusions differently from others?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Every brain is unique. Visual perception is influenced by prior experiences, eye cell density, screen contrast, and attention. In ambiguous illustrations like "The Dress," differences in perceived color depend on whether your brain assumes the dress is lit by blue sky light or yellow indoor light.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 7 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Can animals see optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Yes! Many animals, including cats, dogs, birds, fish, and insects, have been observed reacting to optical illusions. For example, cats will stalk and pounce on the rotating snakes peripheral drift illusion, proving their motion-detection pathways are fooled similarly to ours.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 8 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>What are the 3 types of optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          The three categories are: Literal illusions (images physically different from what compose them), Physiological illusions (neural fatigue from overstimulated sensors), and Cognitive illusions (where top-down assumptions construct phantom lines or shapes).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 9 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do moving optical illusions work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Moving illusions (peripheral drift) utilize asymmetric contrast transitions. Placing specific sequences of white, light-gray, black, and dark-gray segments tricks the direction-selective cells in your retina and visual cortex. The slight delay in processing dark versus light signals is interpreted by the brain as movement.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 10 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Can optical illusions cause headaches?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          In rare cases, looking at highly repetitive patterns with high luminance contrast (like op-art grid stripes) for too long can cause mild eye strain or headaches. This occurs because the visual cortex has to exert significant metabolic energy trying to resolve the conflicting patterns.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Client-side Logic Script -->
  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {

      // 1. Ames Room Slider Simulation
      const amesSlider = document.getElementById('ames-slider');
      const amesCharacter = document.getElementById('ames-character');
      const amesScaleText = document.getElementById('ames-scale-pct');

      if (amesSlider && amesCharacter) {
        amesSlider.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
          const val = parseInt(e.target.value);
          // Scale ranges from 0.40 to 1.40
          const scale = 0.40 + (val / 100) * 1.0;
          
          // Translate X ranges from 50 to 240
          const x = 50 + (val / 100) * 190;
          // Translate Y ranges from 250 to 185
          const y = 250 - (val / 100) * 65;

          amesCharacter.setAttribute('transform', `translate(${x}, ${y}) scale(${scale.toFixed(2)})`);
          amesScaleText.textContent = `Scale: ${scale.toFixed(2)}x`;
        });
      }

      // 2. Motion Aftereffect Experiment Canvas
      const canvas = document.getElementById('mae-canvas');
      const startBtn = document.getElementById('mae-start-btn');
      const stopBtn = document.getElementById('mae-stop-btn');
      const timerOverlay = document.getElementById('mae-timer-overlay');
      const timerText = document.getElementById('mae-timer');

      if (canvas && startBtn && stopBtn) {
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        let animationFrameId = null;
        let yOffset = 0;
        let isStaring = false;
        let isDrifting = false;
        let driftSpeed = 0;
        let lastTime = 0;

        function drawStripes(offset) {
          ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
          const stripeWidth = 20;
          
          for (let x = 0; x < canvas.width; x += stripeWidth * 2) {
            ctx.fillStyle = '#020617';
            ctx.fillRect(x, 0, stripeWidth, canvas.height);
            ctx.fillStyle = '#f8fafc';
            ctx.fillRect(x + stripeWidth, 0, stripeWidth, canvas.height);
          }

          // Draw horizontal stripes scrolling downwards
          for (let y = -stripeWidth * 2; y < canvas.height + stripeWidth * 2; y += stripeWidth * 2) {
            ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.15)'; // Indigo translucent scroll overlay
            ctx.fillRect(0, y + (offset % (stripeWidth * 2)), canvas.width, stripeWidth);
          }
        }

        // Initial render
        drawStripes(0);

        function animateStare(timestamp) {
          if (!lastTime) lastTime = timestamp;
          const delta = timestamp - lastTime;
          lastTime = timestamp;

          yOffset += 0.2 * delta; // Scroll down
          drawStripes(yOffset);
          animationFrameId = requestAnimationFrame(animateStare);
        }

        function animateDrift(timestamp) {
          if (!lastTime) lastTime = timestamp;
          const delta = timestamp - lastTime;
          lastTime = timestamp;

          if (driftSpeed > 0.01) {
            yOffset -= driftSpeed * delta; // Scroll up (aftereffect)
            driftSpeed *= 0.985; // Decelerate
            drawStripes(yOffset);
            animationFrameId = requestAnimationFrame(animateDrift);
          } else {
            isDrifting = false;
            stopBtn.disabled = true;
            startBtn.disabled = false;
          }
        }

        startBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          isStaring = true;
          isDrifting = false;
          startBtn.disabled = true;
          stopBtn.disabled = false;
          timerOverlay.classList.remove('hidden');
          
          let secondsLeft = 20;
          timerText.textContent = secondsLeft;
          
          const interval = setInterval(() => {
            secondsLeft--;
            timerText.textContent = secondsLeft;
            
            if (secondsLeft <= 0) {
              clearInterval(interval);
              timerOverlay.classList.add('hidden');
              // Automatically trigger stop for the drift effect
              stopExperiment();
            }
          }, 1000);

          lastTime = 0;
          animationFrameId = requestAnimationFrame(animateStare);
          
          // Attach interval reference to cancel if manually stopped
          startBtn.dataset.intervalId = interval;
        });

        function stopExperiment() {
          if (!isStaring) return;
          isStaring = false;
          
          // Clear interval if active
          const intervalId = startBtn.dataset.intervalId;
          if (intervalId) {
            clearInterval(parseInt(intervalId));
          }
          timerOverlay.classList.add('hidden');

          cancelAnimationFrame(animationFrameId);

          // Trigger upwards drift simulation
          isDrifting = true;
          driftSpeed = 0.45; // Start speed drifting up
          lastTime = 0;
          animationFrameId = requestAnimationFrame(animateDrift);
        }

        stopBtn.addEventListener('click', stopExperiment);
      }

      // 3. Kanizsa Shapes Toggles
      const togglePacman = document.getElementById('toggle-pacman');
      const toggleAngles = document.getElementById('toggle-angles');
      const togglePhantom = document.getElementById('toggle-phantom');
      const pacmanGroup = document.getElementById('kanizsa-pacmans');
      const anglesGroup = document.getElementById('kanizsa-angles');
      const phantomShape = document.getElementById('kanizsa-phantom');

      if (togglePacman && pacmanGroup) {
        togglePacman.addEventListener('change', (e) => {
          pacmanGroup.style.display = e.target.checked ? 'block' : 'none';
        });
      }
      if (toggleAngles && anglesGroup) {
        toggleAngles.addEventListener('change', (e) => {
          anglesGroup.style.display = e.target.checked ? 'block' : 'none';
        });
      }
      if (togglePhantom && phantomShape) {
        togglePhantom.addEventListener('change', (e) => {
          phantomShape.style.display = e.target.checked ? 'block' : 'none';
        });
      }

      // 4. Visual Pathway Diagram Details Inspector
      const nodes = document.querySelectorAll('.pathway-node');
      const nodeTitle = document.getElementById('info-node-title');
      const nodeRole = document.getElementById('info-node-role');
      const nodeIllusions = document.getElementById('info-node-illusions');
      const nodeIllusionsBox = document.getElementById('info-node-illusions-box');
      
      const nodeDetails = {
        'eye': {
          title: '👁️ Retina & Photoreceptors',
          role: 'Captures photons and converts electromagnetic wavelengths into electrical signals via rods and cones. Employs "lateral inhibition" right at the retina surface to highlight edge differences.',
          illusions: 'Hermann Grid ghost dots, Troxler peripheral fading.'
        },
        'nerve': {
          title: 'Optic Nerve Bundle',
          role: 'A cable of over 1 million ganglion axons carrying sensory electrical impulses. Possesses a physical "blind spot" where the nerve passes through the retina, which the brain automatically patches.',
          illusions: 'Blind spot visual vanishing tests.'
        },
        'lgn': {
          title: '🧠 LGN (Lateral Geniculate Nucleus)',
          role: 'A sensory relay station inside the thalamus. Sorts signals from both eyes into distinct visual channels (parvocellular for detail/color, magnocellular for motion) before sending them to V1.',
          illusions: 'Luminance contrast and brightness distortions.'
        },
        'v1': {
          title: 'V1 — Primary Visual Cortex (Striate)',
          role: 'Located at the rear occipital lobe. Houses orientation-selective simple and complex cells. Resolves basic lines, borders, and spatial frequencies.',
          illusions: 'Zöllner stripes skew, Poggendorff alignment cuts, café wall tiling.'
        },
        'v2': {
          title: 'V2 — Secondary Visual Cortex',
          role: 'Performs initial cognitive segmentation, grouping visual cues, rendering illusory contours, and determining figure-ground separation.',
          illusions: 'Kanizsa Shape Projection, Rubin\'s Vase face/vase flip.'
        },
        'v4': {
          title: 'V4 — Cerebral Color & Form',
          role: 'Responsible for cerebral color processing, shape synthesis, and color constancy adjustments based on assumed ambient light profiles.',
          illusions: 'The ambiguous blue-black/white-gold Dress, Munker-White color spheres.'
        },
        'v5': {
          title: 'V5/MT — Motion-Selective Cortex',
          role: 'Integrates local direction vectors from V1 to calculate global motion speed, trajectory, and speed gradients.',
          illusions: 'Motion Aftereffect (waterfall drift), Peripheral Drift (Rotating Snakes).'
        }
      };

      nodes.forEach(node => {
        node.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const key = node.dataset.node;
          const info = nodeDetails[key];
          
          if (info) {
            // Update UI card
            nodeTitle.textContent = info.title;
            nodeRole.textContent = info.role;
            nodeIllusions.textContent = info.illusions;
            nodeIllusionsBox.classList.remove('hidden');

            // Reset other nodes stroke
            nodes.forEach(n => {
              const c = n.querySelector('circle, rect');
              c.classList.remove('stroke-pink-500');
              c.classList.add('stroke-indigo-500');
            });

            // Highlight active node
            const c = node.querySelector('circle, rect');
            c.classList.remove('stroke-indigo-500');
            c.classList.add('stroke-pink-500');
          }
        });
      });

      // Simulation highlight button
      document.getElementById('fool-brain-btn').addEventListener('click', () => {
        // Highlight V1, V4, V5, V2, LGN
        const targetIds = ['v1-circle', 'v2-circle', 'v4-circle', 'v5-circle'];
        targetIds.forEach(id => {
          const el = document.getElementById(id);
          if (el) {
            el.style.stroke = '#ec4899'; // Pink stroke
            el.style.strokeWidth = '4.5px';
            setTimeout(() => {
              el.style.stroke = '';
              el.style.strokeWidth = '';
            }, 3000);
          }
        });
        alert('💡 Brain areas V1 (lines), V2 (shapes), V4 (colors), and V5 (motion) highlighted! These cortical nodes are the main sensory centers manipulated by visual illusions.');
      });

      // 5. Interactive Brain Quiz Logic
      const quizQuestions = [
        {
          q: "Which visual cortex area is primarily responsible for processing motion?",
          options: ["A. Area V1", "B. Area V4", "C. Area V5/MT"],
          correct: 2,
          explanation: "Area V5 (also called MT) contains motion-selective cells that process direction and speed. Overstimulating this area produces the Motion Aftereffect drift."
        },
        {
          q: "What is Helmholtz's 1867 theory that the brain makes bets about sensory data?",
          options: ["A. Unconscious Inference", "B. Lateral Inhibition", "C. Binocular Rivalry"],
          correct: 0,
          explanation: "Hermann von Helmholtz proposed 'unconscious inference' to explain how the brain constructs a complete visual scene by making unconscious assumptions."
        },
        {
          q: "What neural mechanism enhances edges by having visual cells suppress their neighbors?",
          options: ["A. Predictive Coding", "B. Lateral Inhibition", "C. Troxler Fading"],
          correct: 1,
          explanation: "Lateral Inhibition occurs in the retina, where active light-receptor cells suppress neighboring cells. This makes grid crossings look darker in the Hermann Grid."
        },
        {
          q: "Which brain area resolves illusory shapes like the Kanizsa Triangle?",
          options: ["A. Area V4 (Color)", "B. Area V2 (Grouping)", "C. Retina"],
          correct: 1,
          explanation: "Area V2 contains neurons sensitive to visual grouping and illusory contours, helping the brain visualize borders where none exist."
        },
        {
          q: "Why did evolution preserve optical illusion vulnerabilities in human vision?",
          options: ["A. Shortcuts are faster and usually keep us safe", "B. Human eyes are poorly constructed", "C. The brain has infinite energy"],
          correct: 0,
          explanation: "Visual shortcuts allow the brain to process scenes much faster. Trading minor mathematical accuracy for speed is a major evolutionary survival benefit."
        }
      ];

      let currentQ = 0;
      let score = 0;
      const progressLabel = document.getElementById('quiz-progress-label');
      const scoreLabel = document.getElementById('quiz-score-label');
      const quizContainer = document.getElementById('quiz-container');
      const nextBtn = document.getElementById('quiz-next-btn');

      function loadQuestion(idx) {
        if (idx >= quizQuestions.length) {
          // Quiz End
          progressLabel.textContent = "Quiz Complete!";
          quizContainer.innerHTML = `
            <div class="text-center py-6 space-y-4">
              <h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Final Score: ${score} / ${quizQuestions.length}</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-350">
                ${score === 5 ? "👑 Master Level! Your visual neuroscience knowledge is flawless." : (score >= 3 ? "🌟 Great Job! You understand visual processing pathways." : "🧠 Keep practicing! Visual science is a fascinating journey.")}
              </p>
              <button id="quiz-reset" class="py-2.5 px-6 bg-purple-600 hover:bg-purple-500 rounded-xl text-xs font-bold text-white transition-colors">Retake Quiz</button>
            </div>
          `;
          nextBtn.style.display = 'none';
          
          document.getElementById('quiz-reset').addEventListener('click', () => {
            currentQ = 0;
            score = 0;
            nextBtn.style.display = 'inline-block';
            nextBtn.disabled = true;
            scoreLabel.textContent = `Correct: 0/${quizQuestions.length}`;
            loadQuestion(0);
          });
          return;
        }

        const question = quizQuestions[idx];
        progressLabel.textContent = `Question ${idx + 1} of ${quizQuestions.length}`;
        
        let optionsHtml = '';
        question.options.forEach((opt, oIdx) => {
          optionsHtml += `
            <button class="quiz-option-btn text-left p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 bg-slate-800 hover:bg-slate-700 text-sm text-slate-200 transition-colors w-full" data-oidx="${oIdx}">
              ${opt}
            </button>
          `;
        });

        quizContainer.innerHTML = `
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white">${question.q}</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-3" id="quiz-options">
              ${optionsHtml}
            </div>
            <p class="quiz-explanation hidden text-xs text-slate-400 bg-slate-950 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-850 mt-4 leading-relaxed"></p>
          </div>
        `;

        // Attach events
        const buttons = quizContainer.querySelectorAll('.quiz-option-btn');
        buttons.forEach(btn => {
          btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const chosen = parseInt(btn.dataset.oidx);
            const explanationEl = quizContainer.querySelector('.quiz-explanation');
            
            // Disable further choice clicks
            buttons.forEach(b => b.disabled = true);
            
            if (chosen === question.correct) {
              btn.classList.add('bg-emerald-600/30', 'border-emerald-500', 'text-white');
              score++;
              scoreLabel.textContent = `Correct: ${score}/${quizQuestions.length}`;
              explanationEl.textContent = `✅ CORRECT! ${question.explanation}`;
            } else {
              btn.classList.add('bg-rose-600/30', 'border-rose-500', 'text-white');
              // Highlight correct button
              buttons[question.correct].classList.add('bg-emerald-600/20', 'border-emerald-500/50', 'text-white');
              explanationEl.textContent = `❌ INCORRECT. ${question.explanation}`;
            }

            explanationEl.classList.remove('hidden');
            nextBtn.disabled = false;
          });
        });
      }

      nextBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        currentQ++;
        nextBtn.disabled = true;
        loadQuestion(currentQ);
      });

      // Init Q1
      loadQuestion(0);

      // 6. Searchable Glossary
      const searchInput = document.getElementById('glossary-search');
      const glossaryCards = document.querySelectorAll('.glossary-card');

      if (searchInput) {
        searchInput.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
          const query = e.target.value.toLowerCase().trim();
          
          glossaryCards.forEach(card => {
            const title = card.querySelector('h4').textContent.toLowerCase();
            const desc = card.querySelector('p').textContent.toLowerCase();
            
            if (title.includes(query) || desc.includes(query)) {
              card.style.display = 'flex';
            } else {
              card.style.display = 'none';
            }
          });
        });
      }

      // 7. FAQ Accordions
      const faqToggles = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-toggle');
      faqToggles.forEach(toggle => {
        toggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const content = toggle.nextElementSibling;
          const icon = toggle.querySelector('.faq-icon');
          
          content.classList.toggle('hidden');
          if (content.classList.contains('hidden')) {
            icon.style.transform = 'rotate(0deg)';
          } else {
            icon.style.transform = 'rotate(180deg)';
          }
        });
      });

    });
  </script>

</Layout>
